SIMPLE: litigious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Litigious
<hw>Li*ti"gious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>litigiosus</ets>, fr. <ets>litigium</ets> dispute, quarrel, fr.
<ets>litigare</ets>: cf. F. <ets>litigieux</ets>. See
<er>Litigation</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Inclined to initiate
lawsuits; given to the practice of contending in law; fond of
litigation.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ A pettifogging attorney or a
<xex>litigious</xex> client.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Soldiers find wars, and lawyers find out still⟦br⟧
<qex>Litigious</qex> men, who quarrels move.</q>
<rj><qau>Donne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Quarrelsome; contentious;
argumentative.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Subject to contention; disputable; controvertible;
debatable; doubtful; precarious.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No fences, parted fields, nor marks, nor bounds,⟦br⟧
Distinguished acres of <qex>litigious</qex> grounds.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to legal disputes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor brothers cite to the <qex>litigious</qex> bar.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Litigiously</ent>⟦br⟧
